commits.message:
Allow T_CLASS and generic types to be too_complex

The intial complex shape implementation never allowed objects
other than T_OBJECT to become too complex, unless we run out of
shapes.

I don't see any reason to prevent that.

Ref: https://github.com/ruby/ruby/pull/6931

Fix redefinition of `clock_gettime` and `clock_getres`

winpthreads-git 12.0.0.r720 provides `clock_gettime` and
`clock_getres` as inline functions.

Revert "Try removing building C API specs in CRuby makefiles entirely"

This reverts commit 2a9236366d6016738a756caecab03263565a20c7.
spec/ruby/optional/capi/spec_helper.rb doesn't work well for mingw.
digest.so needs ruby/digest.h which is installed by build-ext
Copy to path with the base name

Handle GC triggering while building the initial `id_to_obj_tbl`

GC can trigger while we build the table, and if it sweeps an object
with an ID, it may not find it in the `id_to_obj` table.

Fix -Wmaybe-uninitialized

[PATCH] zd1201 wireless stat update

	The "dev->get_wireless_stats" field is deprecated and slowly
be surely going away. Most drivers have been updated months
ago. Actually, there is an annoying message for driver still using it,
but it seems that user of zd1201 were not annoyed enough ;-)

Signed-off-by: Jean Tourrilhes <jt@hpl.hp.com>
Signed-off-by: John W. Linville <linville@tuxdriver.com>

[PATCH] hostap: Make hostap_tx_encrypt() static

hostap_tx_encrypt() is used only inside hostap_80211_tx.c and there
are no plans to use it elsewhere in the future either, so let's make
it static. As a bonus, this should silence Coverity scanner from
complaining about bogus FORWARD_NULL case (CID: 274).

Signed-off-by: Jouni Malinen <jkmaline@cc.hut.fi>
Signed-off-by: John W. Linville <linville@tuxdriver.com>

[PATCH] hostap: Fix EAPOL frame encryption

Fixed encrypted of EAPOL frames from wlan#ap interface (hostapd). This
was broken when moving to use new frame control field defines in
net/ieee80211.h. hostapd uses Protected flag, not protocol version
(which was cleared in this function anyway). This fixes WPA group key
handshake and re-authentication.
http://hostap.epitest.fi/bugz/show_bug.cgi?id=126

Signed-off-by: Jouni Malinen <jkmaline@cc.hut.fi>
Signed-off-by: John W. Linville <linville@tuxdriver.com>

issue.title: Support for Secondary Auth Cookie or Chained Auth Logic via Separate Cookie/JWT

labels.name: type/feature
labels.description: Request for adding a new feature

labels.name: status/needs-design
labels.description: Requires formal design process via a discussion or feature request

issue.body:
### Description


I'm trying to implement a way for users to authenticate using Authelia's standard 2FA flow (which works great), but after logging in, I want to set a secondary long-lived cookie (e.g., JWT or signed token) that grants access to a specific subsection of my site from a specific page.

If this is doable/planned in Authelia, then a way to put these in rules so that only specific domains and routes can be accessed, and also see a list of the cookies and revoke them.

Since nginx only allows single auth_request per block, I essentially need to create different blocks if I write my own validator (many apps don't like being served from different subpaths - Grafana being one of them). I could also write a middleware that sits between Authelia and nginx and checks for the cookie, but it's just making it fragile.

Open to other suggestions too. I thought I saw this being mentioned in an issue before, but for the life of me I cannot find it, so I'm creating an feature request for it.

### Use Case


This will mainly be used as a view only dashboard/kiosk type of thing, where it will have read only access.

### Details


Here's the desired flow:

1. User logs in via Authelia and completes 2FA.
2. They're redirected to a portal page where my app sets a separate signed cookie (e.g., X-Portal-Access) after validating that Authelia login was successful. This would obviously need an Authelia API implementation for Authelia to sign it.
3. This cookie is then used to grant access to /some/protected/route — even if the user's Authelia session expires — as long as the cookie remains valid.

The challenge is that NGINX only allows one auth_request, so I can't easily combine Authelia and my own JWT/cookie validation logic in the same location block.

### Documentation


(I used ChatGPT to fix up my grammar, but found it funny that Generative AI was used, lol)

### Generative AI


Yes

### Pre-Submission Checklist


- [x] I agree to follow the [Code of Conduct](http://www.authelia.com/code-of-conduct)

- [x] I have checked for related issues and checked the documentation
